<subSubSection pageId="23" pageNumber="86" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="23.[236,1220,1015,1746]" pageId="23" pageNumber="86">
Remarks. This is an extremely rare species. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Knight" authorityYear="1930" box="[1046,1218,1293,1332]" class="Gastropoda" family="Pseudozygopleuridae" genus="Cyclozyga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coenogastropoda incertae sedis" pageId="23" pageNumber="86" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1046,1218,1293,1332]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="86">Cyclozyga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. (PI. 19 figs 5-8) from 'Kyndalyn' resembles C. 
<taxonomicName authority="Yoo" authorityName="Yoo" box="[237,508,1385,1424]" class="Gastropoda" family="Pseudozygopleuridae" genus="Cyclozyga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coenogastropoda incertae sedis" pageId="23" pageNumber="86" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="sinusigera">
<emphasis box="[237,414,1385,1424]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="86">sinusigera</emphasis>
Yoo
</taxonomicName>
in shell shape and ornamentation, but differs in having closely spaced collabral lirae on teleoconch. Only two specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Knight" authorityYear="1930" box="[902,1076,1478,1516]" class="Gastropoda" family="Pseudozygopleuridae" genus="Cyclozyga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coenogastropoda incertae sedis" pageId="23" pageNumber="86" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[902,1076,1478,1516]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="86">Cyclozyga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. are obtained. The systematic position of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Knight" authorityYear="1930" box="[952,1125,1523,1562]" class="Gastropoda" family="Pseudozygopleuridae" genus="Cyclozyga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coenogastropoda incertae sedis" pageId="23" pageNumber="86" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[952,1125,1523,1562]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="86">Cyclozyga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was discussed by 
<bibRefCitation author="Knight, J. B." box="[492,763,1569,1608]" pageId="23" pageNumber="86" refId="ref25807" refString="Knight, J. B., 1930 a. The gastropods of the St. Louis, Missouri, Pennsylvanian outlier: the Pseudozygopleurinae. Journal of Paleontology 4, Supplement 1, 88 pp." type="book" year="1930">Knight (1930a)</bibRefCitation>
, and 
<bibRefCitation author="Hoare, R. D. &amp; M. T. Sturgeon" pageId="23" pageNumber="86" pagination="850 - 858" refId="ref25615" refString="Hoare, R. D. &amp; M. T. Sturgeon, 1978. The Pennsylvanian gastropod genera Cyclozyga and Hemminthozyga and the classification of the Pseudozygopleuridae. Journal of Paleontology 52 (4): 850 - 858." type="journal article" year="1978">Hoare &amp; Sturgeon (1978)</bibRefCitation>
. The North American species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Knight" authorityYear="1930" box="[950,1123,1615,1654]" class="Gastropoda" family="Pseudozygopleuridae" genus="Cyclozyga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coenogastropoda incertae sedis" pageId="23" pageNumber="86" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[950,1123,1615,1654]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="86">Cyclozyga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have more strongly developed revolving costellae and are more attenuate in form.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
